retrieved_contexts:
resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  ami           = "ami-0c55b159cbfafe1f0"
  instance_type = "t3.micro"
}

Argument Reference: `ami` (Required) - AMI to use for the instance. `instance_type` (Required) - Instance type to use, such as `t3.micro`.

terraform {
  required_providers {
    aws = {
      source  = "hashicorp/aws"
      version = "~> 5.0"
    }
  }
}

required_providers (Optional) - A block declaring which providers are required, and their source and version constraints.

output "instance_public_ip" {
  value       = aws_instance.web.public_ip
  description = "The public IP address of the web server."
}

Argument Reference: `value` (Required)... `depends_on` (Optional) - Explicit dependencies the output should wait on.

terraform {
  backend "s3" {
    bucket         = "my-team-terraform-state"
    key            = "app/terraform.tfstate"
    region         = "us-east-1"
    dynamodb_table = "terraform-lock"
    encrypt        = true
  }
}

Migrate existing local state: terraform init -migrate-state

variable "db_password" {
  type      = string
  sensitive = true
}

sensitive = true isn't full protection: it hides the value from CLI output, but it's still sitting in your state file in plaintext unless your backend encrypts state at rest.
